<section class="blog-3">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-sm-8 col-sm-offset-2">
                <div class="section-main-title">
                    <h3>Social Banks</h3>
                </div>
                

                <div class="quote custom-quote">
                    In a situation of profit, you're blind. Only the dollar signs come in sight. Remove the dollar signs in their eyes and suddenly you will see another world. It's a fascinating world!
                </div>
                <div class="author">Muhammad Yunus</div>

                <div class="text">
                    <p>Social banks are organizations that foster solidarity-based economy to stimulate employment and income generation in their working areas with the objective to overcoming urban poverty and rural</p>
                </div>

                <div class="quote custom-quote">
                    Solidarity-based economy is a different way of producing, selling, buying and exchanging what it takes to live. Without exploiting others, unwittingly taking advantage, without destroying the environment. Cooperating, strengthening the group, each one thinking of the good of all and in their own right.
                </div>
                <div class="quote-author">
                    National Secretary of Solidarity-Based Economy - Ministry of Labour – Brazil
                </div>
                <div class="text">
                    <p>
                        The goal of social banks is to guarantee microcredit to production and local consumption and also provide access to banking services for the residents of the poorest communities, which typically would not have access to them in the traditional banks, based on lack of credit history or financial guarantee and/or physical distance.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The operation is simple: it all starts with a fundraising aiming at generating financial backing. This fundraising can occur in various ways, from resources donated by the community itself or by external actors (companies, organizations, Government). After obtaining the financial backing is made the issue of social currency, usually in a ratio that each official currency generates a social currency of the same value. Once this is done, the user of the social bank will be able to rely on microcredit that is received in the social currency in circulation in his neighborhood or town.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        From there the user uses the social currency in circulation in his neighborhood or town. In local trade, he earns discount by paying with that money. The merchant can undo the exchange in the Social Bank, if it has need to shop outside the community.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Thus, the wealth lies within the neighborhood, because the social currency payment has no value outside of there. The idea is to make the resources of that community can circulate for as long as possible inside it expanding the power of the local trade, increasing wealth, generating employment and income in the area. The social currency, therefore, becomes an essential component in the strategies of community banks. Credits can help in the economic growth of the district or region through the creation of new wealth. Local currencies guarantee development, promoting that wealth to circulate in the community itself.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In November 2009 the Central Bank of Brazil signed a deed of partnership with National Secretary of Solidarity-Based Economy - Ministry of Labour (Federal Government) to create a technical note to social currencies, creating a kind of "official position" of the Brazilian Government on the local social currencies circulating. The process is still in progress, but the Central Bank's relationship with the Brazilian Network of Community Banks, with regard to the use of social currencies, has been significantly positive.
                    <p>                    
                        In 2013 there were 103 local social currencies circulating in Brazil. According to data from the Brazilian Network of Community Banks, in 2012 was circulating in Brazil the value of R$ 500,000 exchanged in social currencies, with an estimated 350,000 people using them.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

